{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"920"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/920"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.08,0.11,0.22,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99976"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"574"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99976"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 57-year-old man presents with a painless swelling on the thenar eminence of his right hand (Image). This has been present for three weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spider bite","Verruca","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom the rapidity of progression of this lesion, it is most likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratoacanthoma\u003C/strong\u003E (KA). Some consider KA to be a variant of squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) whilst others group this with other benign tumours. Basal cell carcinomas and squamous cell carcinomas usually grow at a much slower rate. The exception to this might be more rapid growth in the immunocompromised patient. Most clinicians will manage this lesion as a well-differentiated SCC and recommend early surgical resection. The diagnosis is usually made on their clinical behaviour: keratoacanthomas appearing within days or weeks and then regressing and disappearing just as rapidly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lesion is unlikely to be a spider bite - which would be painful and not persistent for this long. A verruca - or plantar wart - is typically found on the sole of the foot and is often associated with pain, particularly when pressure is applied. They tend not have a central core, as shown in this lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Surgical resection is the recommended treatment for keratoacanthoma."],"references":["Kwiek B, Schwartz RA. Keratoacanthoma (KA): An update and review. J Am Acad Dematol 2016; 74:1222-33."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"920"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18650"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18650"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/143ec01d-af40-4130